<font color="#FF0000">MOTIVATION</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb 15 16:28:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art<br><br>
I really thought a lot about your last post.  I don't know if the fact that we went in the service at different times had anything to do with the differences between us or not.  Your impressions of protestors and our national leaders had you one up on me as I never even notice either groups.  Those in my graduating class, I had never even discussed Vietnam or draft deferments or how to obtain a 4f status.  You are right in respect to how many, if most, of us were just caught in our own little world, though.  Which probably made us easy draft bait.<br><br>
I have identified two areas, from this site, which rankles me to no end.  The first is when I hear that no returning vets were &quot;spat&quot; upon.  I don't think there are many combat vets who experienced a positive homecoming.  But there are those out there who want to insist that these things that happened to you or I or other vets never really happened.  There is nothing that we can do about those folks.  They have their reasons for believing this, though, for the life of me I cannot fathom what.  And there are those out there who recognize that there was some abuse of the vets, but want to minimize the degree and effects of said abuse.  Again, there is nothing to be done.<br><br>
The second thing that truely pisses me off is this line that we had the &quot;duty&quot; to be aware, to know, that the Vietnam war was wrong, and that if you did chose to go, indeed, you were an immoral person because you chose to be.  I just wonder how old the anti-war activists were when they became &quot;enlightened&quot;.  What year were they in college, what year of the war?  When you are a junior or senior in college, or in a master's program, you have the luxury of a few more years under your belt to be so astute and self-righteous.  It was much easier in '71 to have much more knowledgeable about the &quot;morality&quot; of the war than in '67.<br><br>
And there are those who want to ignore the fact that for many of us, options available were just not there.  A line that sticks to me was from Alex Hernandez, when he remarked that military service was a way out of the ghetto.  This I can identify with.<br><br>
I can identify with you in the respect that you wanted to make a difference.  When I made the decision to volunteer for the draft, I also wanted to make a difference.  At that time, at least I was aware enough to know that I was either going to die on the street or end up in prison.  I was aware that I had done absolutely nothing positive for myself or for society.  I wanted to change all those things.  But to stick around where I grew up, that would have made it impossible.  The service was the only thing available to make it happen for me.<br><br>
In basic training, I had assumed that I was going to be 11 Boo, a rifleman.  I thought at that time, maybe I could contribute by helping to keep my &quot;buddies&quot; alive.  When I got my orders for medic school, I knew then that that was what I was meant for, that was the way to do something positive, the way I could make just a little bit of difference.<br><br>
Aside from all the above, there is a part of me who wants to believe that the protestors were right, that their motivations were, indeed, altruistic. If I cannot find this altruistic nature within the protest community, where will I be able to find it?  It would be a shitty, shitty thing to believe that what motivates them, us and everbody else is all that I would consider negative.<br><br>
Whats even shittier, is that I haven't found anything yet to justify changing these views.<br><br>
You're right.  It still hurts!
